00:50:48.700 --> 00:50:51.950
So how do you reconcile being
flexible and seeing what's

00:50:51.950 --> 00:50:55.430
out there, and allowing yourself
to see the possibilities

00:50:55.430 --> 00:50:57.160
with being deliberate
and actually moving

00:50:57.160 --> 00:50:58.870
in the direction
that you want to go?

00:50:58.870 --> 00:50:59.620
DORIE CLARK: Yeah.

00:50:59.620 --> 00:51:01.680
So it's an important question.

00:51:01.680 --> 00:51:06.070
And in many ways, it's similar
to the going wide versus going

00:51:06.070 --> 00:51:07.640
narrow.

00:51:07.640 --> 00:51:10.050
I would say in
general, we can play

00:51:10.050 --> 00:51:14.120
choose to play to our strengths,
whatever our strength is.

00:51:14.120 --> 00:51:16.550
However, there is a way
to bring them together.

00:51:16.550 --> 00:51:19.990
I mean, certainly in terms of
a lot of the career research

00:51:19.990 --> 00:51:23.260
that I do, one piece
of advice that I

00:51:23.260 --> 00:51:26.590
would give to the
professionals that I

00:51:26.590 --> 00:51:28.840
counsel and work with in
my consulting business,

00:51:28.840 --> 00:51:31.360
is, have a plan.

00:51:31.360 --> 00:51:33.340
But treat it as a hypothesis.

00:51:33.340 --> 00:51:35.910
It's something that
you're moving toward so

00:51:35.910 --> 00:51:37.990
that you are moving
towards something,

00:51:37.990 --> 00:51:40.300
so that you have some
degree of forward momentum.

00:51:40.300 --> 00:51:42.780
But don't allow
it to lock you in.

00:51:42.780 --> 00:51:45.780
If you see something over
to the side that is better,

00:51:45.780 --> 00:51:48.320
or is more interesting, or is
something that you literally

00:51:48.320 --> 00:51:51.340
just could not have predicted
because you couldn't have even

00:51:51.340 --> 00:51:55.430
seen it until you reached the
halfway point in your march

00:51:55.430 --> 00:51:58.660
toward that new thing, then
feel free to veer off and go

00:51:58.660 --> 00:51:59.740
do that.

00:51:59.740 --> 00:52:03.220
But always have something
that at least provisionally

00:52:03.220 --> 00:52:05.030
you're working
toward, so that you're

00:52:05.030 --> 00:52:07.840
able to enjoy the benefits
of forward momentum

00:52:07.840 --> 00:52:09.555
and seeing things
from new vistas

00:52:09.555 --> 00:52:12.273
that you previously
wouldn't have been able to.

00:52:12.273 --> 00:52:13.260
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

00:52:13.260 --> 00:52:16.110
DORIE CLARK: Thank you.

