00:53:21.360 --> 00:53:22.720
with a big company.

00:53:22.720 --> 00:53:23.470
DORIE CLARK: Yeah.

00:53:23.470 --> 00:53:24.530
Really important.

00:53:24.530 --> 00:53:26.780
So there's actually a
couple of questions at play.

00:53:26.780 --> 00:53:29.680
One is the personal
branding question.

00:53:29.680 --> 00:53:32.720
How do you get known
and get credibility

00:53:32.720 --> 00:53:36.030
as being the driving force
behind a certain idea?

00:53:36.030 --> 00:53:39.570
And then the other
is the question of,

00:53:39.570 --> 00:53:43.660
where is the best home
for that idea in terms

00:53:43.660 --> 00:53:46.180
of operationalizing
it, and actually making

00:53:46.180 --> 00:53:49.240
sure that it has the resources
necessary to be successful.

00:53:52.140 --> 00:53:56.950
In the Silicon Valley ecosystem,
acqui-hires are a big thing

00:53:56.950 --> 00:54:01.360
now, where companies,
as you guys well know,

00:54:01.360 --> 00:54:04.450
large companies will
snap up a smaller company

00:54:04.450 --> 00:54:06.240
because they want the
development talent.

00:54:06.240 --> 00:54:09.050
And they will shutter the
projects with impunity,

00:54:09.050 --> 00:54:12.820
and say, OK, fellas, now
you're working on this.

00:54:12.820 --> 00:54:15.700
And that's a real thing.

00:54:15.700 --> 00:54:18.860
So I think that in a
technical sense, about what

00:54:18.860 --> 00:54:22.120
is necessary for the
success of an idea,

00:54:22.120 --> 00:54:24.740
I think that it's important
to keep in mind a few things.

00:54:24.740 --> 00:54:28.860
Number one, is it feasible
to do the idea on your own?

00:54:28.860 --> 00:54:31.090
Sometimes, literally,
it's not, because you

00:54:31.090 --> 00:54:34.800
need to have data or
access to other resources

00:54:34.800 --> 00:54:36.930
that only a big
company could provide.

00:54:36.930 --> 00:54:40.140
If you realize that in
three months, or six months,

00:54:40.140 --> 00:54:43.470
or a year, you were going to be
hitting a wall that you can't

00:54:43.470 --> 00:54:47.160
surmount because you literally
don't have access to the tools

00:54:47.160 --> 00:54:49.890
you need, then it probably
does fundamentally

00:54:49.890 --> 00:54:54.050
need to be done within the
confines of a larger system.

00:54:54.050 --> 00:54:58.450
If you do decide to
partner with a company,

00:54:58.450 --> 00:54:59.910
then it's a question
of making sure

00:54:59.910 --> 00:55:02.760
that you have contracts
and legal protections,

00:55:02.760 --> 00:55:06.910
as much as you possibly can,
that validate this idea is not

00:55:06.910 --> 00:55:09.990
going to be shuttered,
and that you have ways

00:55:09.990 --> 00:55:13.050
of protecting it and keeping
it as an ongoing concern,

00:55:13.050 --> 00:55:16.430
perhaps with a sort
of special mandate.

00:55:16.430 --> 00:55:18.140
When it comes to
your personal brand,

00:55:18.140 --> 00:55:19.640
one of the things
that I'll advise--

00:55:19.640 --> 00:55:23.300
and I'll just wrap up because
we're getting the curtain

00:55:23.300 --> 00:55:28.570
warning here momentarily-- but
one of the things that I think

00:55:28.570 --> 00:55:31.360
is important for all
of us to be aware of

00:55:31.360 --> 00:55:36.590
is the amazing resource
that is content creation.

00:55:36.590 --> 00:55:39.090
Sometimes people come to me
and they say, well, you know,

00:55:39.090 --> 00:55:40.510
I have these great ideas.

00:55:40.510 --> 00:55:43.280
But I don't want to talk
about them because someone

00:55:43.280 --> 00:55:45.240
might steal them.

00:55:45.240 --> 00:55:48.660
And you hear this
a lot from people.

00:55:48.660 --> 00:55:50.860
And so my asterisk
on this, OK, sure.

00:55:50.860 --> 00:55:54.490
If you have this amazing,
patentable engineering

00:55:54.490 --> 00:55:55.720
innovation, great.

00:55:55.720 --> 00:55:58.700
Go patent it, go do that,
go protect that first.

00:55:58.700 --> 00:56:00.260
But if you have
an idea, and it's

00:56:00.260 --> 00:56:03.660
an idea about the nature
of leadership or something

00:56:03.660 --> 00:56:06.160
like that, you can't patent it.

00:56:06.160 --> 00:56:10.947
But it doesn't go anywhere
if you don't talk about it.

00:56:10.947 --> 00:56:13.280
Is there going to be a risk
that someone might steal it?

00:56:13.280 --> 00:56:14.110
Maybe.

00:56:14.110 --> 00:56:18.390
But I will tell you the very
best insurance against it

00:56:18.390 --> 00:56:21.950
is for you to be everywhere
talking about it, because if I

00:56:21.950 --> 00:56:24.090
came to you and
said, hey, I have

00:56:24.090 --> 00:56:27.550
a really great idea for a book
about women's empowerment.

00:56:27.550 --> 00:56:31.050
It's called "Lean In," you
would laugh in my face,

00:56:31.050 --> 00:56:32.890
and you'd say, I
think that's been

00:56:32.890 --> 00:56:37.610
done by Sheryl Sandberg, Dorie,
and it doesn't go any further.

00:56:37.610 --> 00:56:40.010
Everyone knows that's her idea.

00:56:40.010 --> 00:56:44.280
And so the antidote to
anyone stealing your ideas,

00:56:44.280 --> 00:56:48.596
or your idea dying, for that
matter, is to get the word out.

00:56:48.596 --> 00:56:50.970
And so I would say if you want
to be known and associated

00:56:50.970 --> 00:56:53.680
for something, go
nuts with blogging,

00:56:53.680 --> 00:56:55.570
with content creation,
being out there,

00:56:55.570 --> 00:56:59.140
touting it, so that your name
is almost inextricably entwined

00:56:59.140 --> 00:56:59.660
with it.

00:56:59.660 --> 00:57:02.070
And then that way, whether
you get acquired, partner

00:57:02.070 --> 00:57:05.220
with somebody, or not, you're
going to be known as the go

00:57:05.220 --> 00:57:07.640
to person behind that idea.

00:57:07.640 --> 00:57:10.010
So thank you so much
for your question.

00:57:10.010 --> 00:57:11.510
Thank you, everybody,
for having me.

00:57:11.510 --> 00:57:13.770
And have a great day.

